About the output
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Every step begins with a header like:

    Stepped at PC = 0x00400128:
        memory[0x00400128] = 0x214affff   →   addi $t2, $t2, -1
        source line 118: addi $t2, $t2, -1

What each part means:

  PC = 0xADDR
        The program counter — the address in memory of the
        instruction that just executed.

  memory[0xADDR] = 0xWORD
        The 32-bit machine code stored at that address. This
        is what the CPU's decoder reads.

  →  real-instruction
        The disassembled form — what the CPU actually ran,
        with registers shown in ABI names ($t2, $sp, $a0)
        rather than register numbers.

  source line N: ...
        The line from your assembly file the assembler read
        for this instruction. If it doesn't match the real
        instruction on the line above, you wrote a pseudo-
        instruction (e.g. `la $t7, dst` expands to `lui` +
        `ori` — the source line appears once but two real
        instructions get narrated).

Placeholder notation in pseudo-op descriptions and structural
explanations:

  $rs, $rt, $rd, shamt
        Field names from the MIPS instruction encoding —
        $rs = first source register, $rt = second source or
        target register, $rd = destination register, shamt =
        shift amount.  When you see these in a pseudo-op's
        general-form description (e.g. "set $rd to ..."),
        they refer to whatever registers you wrote in YOUR
        source line.  The disassembled "What it did" lines
        substitute the concrete register names in place of
        these placeholders.

(This header is shown once per session. Higher `-explain`
levels add per-instruction narration after the header.)

