Stepped at PC = 0x00400000:
    memory[0x00400000] = 0x8fa40000   →   lw $a0, 0($sp)
    source line 183: 	lw $a0 0($sp)		# argc

  Category: Data transfer
    Move data between registers and memory.  MIPS is
    load/store — math never operates on memory directly.
    (COD §2.3, §2.9.)
  Modifiers in `lw`:
    `w` — word width: the load/store transfers 32 bits — one full
          register's worth.  MIPS is word-aligned, so the
          effective address must be a multiple of 4.
  What it did:
    Load Word — read a 32-bit word from memory at the effective address; placed the result in $a0.
    Effective address = $sp + 0  =  0x7fffffdc + 0  =  0x7fffffdc.
  Inputs (before this step):
    $sp = 0x7fffffdc  (decimal 2147483612)
    offset = 0  (0x0000)
    memory at 0x7fffffdc = 0x00000001
  Wrote:
    $a0:  0x00000001  →  0x00000001   (decimal 1)
  Try it yourself:
    print $sp
    print $a0
    print 0x7fffffdc       # inspect that memory
    print 0($sp)           # same memory, using the N($reg) form you wrote
    (the load did happen — the memory value matched the prior register value)
  PC:  0x00400000  →  0x00400004


